  "simpleAction": {
    "format": "rules-card",
    "title": "Simple Action",
    "subtitle": "Action Opposition",
    "blocks": [
      "A simple action is not opposed. Calculate your dice pool and roll results as normal."
    ],
    "source": {
      "book": "DtR",
      "page": 189
    }
  },
  "instantAction": {
    "format": "rules-card",
    "title": "Instant Action",
    "subtitle": "Action Time",
    "blocks": [
      "An instant action is resolved with a single roll. Unless otherwise noted, an instant action only takes a few seconds and takes up your turn in an action scene."
    ],
    "source": {
      "book": "DtR",
      "page": 189
    }
  },
  "extendedAction": {
    "format": "rules-card big-rules-card",
    "title": "Extended Action",
    "subtitle": "Action Time",
    "blocks": [
      "An extended action is resolved with multiple rolls made over a period of time and, as such, is not usually an option in action scenes unless otherwise noted.",
      "The Storyteller determines how many total successes are required to succeed at an extended action. The Storyteller also determines the <strong>interval</strong> between rolls.",
      "Once you determine these factors, make a number of rolls, counting up the total number of successes across all your rolls. If you earn the required number of successes before you run out of time, you accomplish your goal.",
      "You can make a total number of rolls equal to your base dice pool for the action, before factoring in any modifiers.",
      "<strong>Roll Results</strong>",
      "<span class='tooltip-list-item'><strong>Success:</strong> Add the successes earned on the roll to your running total. Work with the Storyteller to determine what steps you have taken towards your goal.</span>",
      "<span class='tooltip-list-item'><strong>Exceptional Success:</strong> Choose one: reduce the total number of successes required by your Skill dots; reduce the interval between each roll by a quarter; or apply the effects of an exceptional success to the entire action when you complete your goal.</span>",
      "<span class='tooltip-list-item'><strong>Failure:</strong> You face a setback. The Storyteller offers you a choice: Take a Condition of their choice, or abandon the action. You can offer a different Condition if you think it makes sense. If you refuse or cannot agree on a Condition, you lose all accumulated successes.</span>",
      "<span class='tooltip-list-item'><strong>Dramatic Failure:</strong> Lose all accumulated successes. In addition, the first roll on a subsequent attempt suffers a &minus;2 die penalty..</span>",
    ],
    "source": {
      "book": "DtR",
      "page": 189
    }
  },
  "reflexiveAction": {
    "format": "rules-card",
    "title": "Reflexive Action",
    "subtitle": "Action Time",
    "blocks": [
      "A reflexive action takes no appreciable time or effort, and resolves in a single roll, or may not require a roll at all.",
      "In an action scene, you can take reflexive actions on other characters' turns, and reflexive actions don't take up your turn.",
      "Contesting someone else's action is always reflexive."
    ],
    "source": {
      "book": "DtR",
      "page": 189
    }
  },
  "resisted": {
    "format": "rules-card",
    "title": "Resisted",
    "subtitle": "Action Opposition",
    "blocks": [
      "A resisted action is opposed by one of your target's Resistance Attributes (Stamina, Resolve or Composure), or their Defense.",
      "Subtract the appropriate trait from your dice pool, then roll and calculate results as normal."
    ],
    "source": {
      "book": "DtR",
      "page": 189
    }
  },
  "contested": {
    "format": "rules-card",
    "title": "Contested",
    "subtitle": "Action Opposition",
    "blocks": [
      "A contested action is opposed by a reflexive roll made by your target.",
      "Calculate your dice pool and roll results as normal. Then, your target rolls a dice pool specified by how they contest the action.",
      "If your total successes exceed the target's, your action succeeds; if their total successes exceed yours, your action fails.",
      "If you and your target roll the same number of successes, both of you reroll the same pools until someone comes out on top."
    ],
    "source": {
      "book": "DtR",
      "page": 189
    }
  },
  "size": {
    "format": "rules-card",
    "title": "Size",
    "blocks": [
      "How large an object or character is. Objects smaller than <strong>Size 1</strong> can fit entirely in a person's palm.",
      "<img src='../assets/images/rules/size.jpg' />"
    ],
    "source": {
      "book": "CoD",
      "page": 26
    }
  },
  "durability": {
    "format": "rules-card",
    "title": "Durability",
    "subtitle": "Object Trait",
    "blocks": [
      "How hard the object is to damage.",
      "Subtract Durability from any damage inflicted on the object.",
      "Durability has no effect against attacks that inflict aggravated damage.",
      "Once an object has taken more damage than its Durability, anyone using the object suffers a &minus;1 die penalty.",
      "<img src='../assets/images/rules/durability.jpg' />"
    ],
    "source": {
      "book": "DtR",
      "page": 207
    }
  },
  "structure": {
    "format": "rules-card",
    "title": "Structure",
    "subtitle": "Object Trait",
    "blocks": [
      "An object's Structure equals its Durability + Size.",
      "Each point of damage (after Durability is subtracted) reduces Structure by one point. Objects do not differentiate between bashing and lethal damage.",
      "When an object's Structure hits 0, it is destroyed."
    ],
    "source": {
      "book": "DtR",
      "page": 207
    }
  },
  "freeDot": {
    "format": "rules-card",
    "title": "Free Dot",
    "subtitle": "Granted by Origin",
    "blocks": [
      "This dot was granted for free by {{NAME}}'s Origin, and does not need to be entangled with a Scar.",
      "It can be used to increase the Magnitude of a Variation without having to raise the Magnitude of the entangled Scar, or it can be used to possess a one-dot Variation with no entangled Scar at all."
    ],
    "source": {
      "book": "DtR",
      "page": 107
    }
  },
  "brokenDot": {
    "format": "rules-card",
    "title": "Unstable Dot",
    "subtitle": "Starting Instability",
    "blocks": [
      "At the beginning of each story, {{NAME}} suffers a number of minor Instabilities equal to the Magnitude of {{his}} highest-rated Variation. This number is represented by dots marked in this fashion."
    ],
    "source": {
      "book": "DtR",
      "page": 87
    }
  },
  "armor": {
    "format": "rules-card",
    "title": "Armor",
    "blocks": [
      "Armor provides protection against attacks, including bullets, knives, and fangs.",
      "Armor comes in one of two types: <strong>general</strong> and <strong>ballistic</strong>.",
      "<span class='tooltip-list-item'><strong>General Armor:</strong> Each point of general armor reduces the total damage taken by one point, starting with the most severe type of damage.</span>",
      "<span class='tooltip-list-item'><strong>Ballistic Armor:</strong> Each point of ballistic armor downgrades one point of lethal damage from firearms to bashing.</span>",
      "If armor has both ballistic and general ratings, apply the ballistic armor first.",
      "When applying armor to an attack inflicting lethal damage, you always suffer at least one point of bashing damage from the shock of the blow."
    ],
    "source": {
      "book": "DtR",
      "page": 199
    }
  }
}

